The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 DCM Shriram Consolidated has decided to issue bonus shares to its shareholders and split the equity shares of the company. The shareholders have approved the issue of bonus shares in the proportion of one equity share for every share held. They have also given nod to share split in 1:5 ratio ? that is, one equity shares of Rs 10 each into 5 equity shares of Rs 2 each, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. 

 Graphite India will raise $40 million from overseas markets through unsubordinated, unsecured foreign currency convertible bonds. The five-year FCCBs are convertible into equity shares at Rs 330.938 per share and carry a coupon of one per cent per annum, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Xenitis group has tied up with Supertron Electronic Ltd for marketing its computer components. Xenitis will supply Supertron one lakh pieces each of computer cabinets, SMPS, keyboards, mouse and speakers every month to its channels and original equipment manufacturers. 

 Trend micro Inc has upgraded its four-year-old liaison office in India into a 100 per cent subsidiary. The company has recorded a 122 per cent turnover growth in 2004-05. The new entity, Trend Micro India Pvt Ltd, will double its headcount to 20 professionals by 2007, a company release said.

 Jindal Saw has approved 25 per cent increase in the FII investment limit in the company. The shareholders have approved the proposal for raising the limit of FII investment from 24 per cent to 49 per cent of the paid-up capital of the company.

 Symantec Corp has signed an agreement to acquire Wholesecurity Inc. The transaction is expected to close in October. Wholesecurity provides protection solution for computer virus and security technology. 

 Air-India and Tourism Malaysia have launched a joint package, Truly Festival ? Truly, for travelling to Malaysia from India. The 3-night package costs Rs 14,999 per person and is valid ex-Delhi and Mumbai is on till November 30.

 Hewlett-Packard has launched a new range of Presario desktops with an Intel Pentium 4 processor. The computer has 128 MB DDR and 40 GB hard disk. The PC is priced at Rs 17,990 and the Compaq Presario Sg008IL at Rs 19,990.

 Zebra Technologies has appointed Spaceage Telecom as its reseller in Calcutta to grow its bar codes amp; RFID products. in eastern India.

